            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How Tennessee income tax works</h2>
              <p>
                Tennessee is one of a handful of states without a broad-based
                income tax on wages. For most residents, that means:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >No state tax on wages, salaries, or self-employment
                    income</strong
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>No current Hall income tax</strong> on interest and
                  dividends (fully repealed starting 2021)
                </li>
                <li>
                  You still pay <strong>federal income tax</strong> and
                  <strong>FICA</strong> (Social Security and Medicare)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your overall tax burden comes mainly from
                  <strong>sales tax</strong> and <strong>property tax</strong>
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. State income tax: $0 on wages</h3>
              <p>
                Tennessee’s constitution and statutes do not impose a general
                tax on earned income. Historically, the state levied the
                <strong>Hall income tax</strong> on certain interest and
                dividend income, but it was phased out and fully repealed for
                tax years beginning January 1, 2021.
              </p>
              <p>Our calculator therefore assumes:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Tennessee state income tax = $0</strong> for current
                  years, regardless of wage income.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Sales tax in Tennessee</h3>
              <p>
                Instead of income tax, Tennessee relies heavily on sales tax.
                The system has two layers:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>State sales tax:</strong> 7% on most taxable goods and
                  some services
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Local sales tax:</strong> up to 2.75% added by
                  counties and cities
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                That means total general sales tax rates typically range from
                about <strong>8.5% to 9.75%</strong>. Many large counties
                (Davidson, Shelby, Knox, Hamilton) are at the maximum
                <strong>9.75%</strong>.
              </p>

              <p>In the calculator we estimate your annual sales tax as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Sales tax} = \text{Taxable spending} \times
                  \frac{\text{County sales tax rate}}{100} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                “Taxable spending” is the portion of your budget that goes to
                items subject to the full sales tax rate (for example, clothing,
                electronics, dining out). Groceries and some other items may be
                taxed at lower rates or exempt; you can adjust the spending
                input to reflect your own situation.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Property tax in Tennessee</h3>
              <p>
                Property taxes are set and collected by counties and
                municipalities. Tennessee’s effective property tax rates are
                <strong>moderate compared with the national average</strong>,
                but they vary by location.
              </p>
              <p>
                To keep the calculator flexible, we use an
                <strong>effective property tax rate</strong> you can adjust with
                a slider. The estimate is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Property tax} = \text{Home value} \times
                  \frac{\text{Effective property tax rate}}{100} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, a $350,000 home at a 0.7% effective rate would
                generate about $2,450 in annual property tax.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Federal income tax estimation</h3>
              <p>
                Even though Tennessee does not tax your wages, the IRS still
                does. To give you a realistic picture of your total tax burden,
                we estimate your <strong>federal income tax</strong> using:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your <strong>filing status</strong> (single, married filing
                  jointly, head of household)
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your total income (wages + interest/dividends + other income)
                </li>
                <li>
                  The <strong>standard deduction</strong> for the selected tax
                  year
                </li>
                <li>Current federal tax brackets for that year</li>
              </ul>

              <p>We use a simplified version of the federal tax formula:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  1. <strong>Adjusted gross income (AGI)</strong> ≈ wages +
                  interest/dividends + other income
                </p>
                <p>
                  2. <strong>Taxable income</strong> = max(0, AGI − standard
                  deduction)
                </p>
                <p>
                  3. <strong>Federal tax</strong> = sum of bracketed tax on
                  taxable income
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator does <strong>not</strong> account for itemized
                deductions, tax credits, retirement contributions, or other
                adjustments, so your actual federal tax may be lower or higher.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Total effective tax rate</h3>
              <p>
                Finally, we combine the components to show your overall tax
                burden:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Total tax} = \text{Federal income tax} + \text{Sales
                  tax} + \text{Property tax} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Effective tax rate} = \frac{\text{Total
                  tax}}{\text{Total income}} \times 100\% \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Tennessee income tax</h2>

              <h3>Does Tennessee tax Social Security benefits?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Tennessee does not tax Social Security benefits. However,
                Social Security may still be taxable at the federal level
                depending on your total income.
              </p>

              <h3>Are retirement distributions taxed in Tennessee?</h3>
              <p>
                Tennessee does not tax pensions, 401(k) withdrawals, or IRA
                distributions at the state level. They are still subject to
                federal income tax rules.
              </p>

              <h3>
                How does Tennessee compare to other states with no income tax?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Like other no-income-tax states (such as Florida, Texas, and
                Nevada), Tennessee relies more heavily on sales and property
                taxes. Tennessee’s combined sales tax rates are among the
                highest in the country, while its property tax burden is closer
                to the national average.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Is this calculator a substitute for professional tax advice?
              </h3>
